SIMPLE: infinite
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infinite
<hw>In"fi*nite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>infinitus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>infini</ets>. See <er>In-</er> not,
and <er>Finite</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Unlimited or boundless, in time or space; <as>as,
<ex>infinite</ex> duration or distance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatever is finite, as finite, will admit of no comparative
relation with infinity; for whatever is less than <qex>infinite</qex> is
still infinitely distant from infinity; and lower than
<qex>infinite</qex> distance the lowest or least can not sink.</q>
<rj><qau>H. Brooke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Without limit in power, capacity, knowledge, or
excellence; boundless; immeasurably or inconceivably great; perfect;
<as>as, the <ex>infinite</ex> wisdom and goodness of God</as>; --
opposed to <ant>finite</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great is our Lord, and of great power; his understanding is
<qex>infinite</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxlvii. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O God, how <qex>infinite</qex> thou art!</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Indefinitely large or extensive; great; vast;
immense; gigantic; prodigious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Infinite</qex> riches in a little room.</q>
<rj><qau>Marlowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which <qex>infinite</qex> calamity shall cause⟦br⟧
To human life.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Greater than any assignable
quantity of the same kind; -- said of certain quantities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Capable of endless repetition; --
said of certain forms of the canon, called also <altname>perpetual
fugues</altname>, so constructed that their ends lead to their
beginnings, and the performance may be incessantly repeated.</def>
<rj><au>Moore (Encyc. of Music).</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Boundless; immeasurable; illimitable;
interminable; limitless; unlimited; endless; eternal.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infinite</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Infinite
<hw>In"fi*nite</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is
infinite; boundless space or duration; infinity;
boundlessness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not till the weight is heaved from off the air, and the thunders
roll down the horizon, will the serene light of God flow upon us, and
the blue <qex>infinite</qex> embrace us again.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Martineau.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>An infinite quantity or
magnitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An infinity; an incalculable or very great
number.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Glittering chains, embroidered richly o'er⟦br⟧
With <qex>infinite</qex> of pearls and finest gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Fanshawe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The Infinite Being; God; the Almighty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>infinite loop</ent>⟦br⟧
